  "summary": "Patrick and Julia Simmons discuss their relationship to Letitia Blacklock. Patrick describes himself as a distant relative, while Letitia admits she has forgotten the names and number of Eleanor's children until Patrick's arrival. Observing this, Miss Marple notes that Letitia has not seen her young relatives before, a detail she believes would interest Inspector Corcoran.\n\nElsewhere, Edmund Swetnam approaches Philippa while she is transplanting winter lettuce. Edmund claims he is visiting on business to trade honey for zucchinis at the request of Mrs. Lucas, but he uses this as an excuse to pursue Philippa romantically. He attempts to engage her in deep conversation by quoting Tennyson and questioning her about her past and her feelings. Edmund pressures Philippa to discuss her deceased husband, who was killed in Italy, and proposes that they marry so she can continue her gardening while he writes books. Philippa rejects his proposal, telling him that he does not know her. Edmund responds with nonsensical, mournful rhymes before asking for a zucchini just as Mrs. Lucas approaches. Meanwhile, Constable Fletcher is noted to be overseeing the security of the small estate.",
